# Plan File Standards

**CRITICAL FORMAT REQUIREMENT:** Every `.plan.md` file MUST use the exact format defined in this rule. The user reviews plans against this format and `/task-manager` requires it to append the execution strategy. Read this rule BEFORE writing any `.plan.md` content.

Every `.plan.md` file must include a **plan log header** immediately after the YAML frontmatter and before the main heading.

## Plan Log Header Format

```markdown
> **Plan** | `<plan-name>`
> **Status** | `<status>` | **Priority** | `<priority>`
> **Created** | `<YYYY-MM-DD>` | **Updated** | `<YYYY-MM-DD>`
> **Author** | `<author>` | **Environment** | `<environments>`
> **PR/Ticket** | `<link or —>` | **Rollback** | `<Yes/No/N/A>`
> **Phase** | `<current-phase>` | **Wave** | `<current-wave or —>`
> **Strategy Version** | `<integer or —>` | **Active Tasks** | `<task IDs or —>`
> **Blocked Tasks** | `<task IDs or —>`
```

**Phase values:** `1-Planning` | `2-Approval` | `3-Execution` | `4-Review` | `5-PR` | `Complete`

**Strategy Version** starts at `1` when the task-manager creates the Execution Strategy. It increments on every plan revision. The orchestrator executes only the latest approved version. Set to `—` before the Execution Strategy exists.

**Active Tasks** and **Blocked Tasks** are updated by the orchestrator during Phase 3. Set to `—` outside Phase 3.

Agents update these fields at every phase transition. On session resume, read them to determine where to pick up.

## Status Lifecycle

| Status | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| `Draft` | Plan created, still being designed or edited |
| `In Review` | Submitted for peer/team review |
| `Approved` | Reviewed and approved for execution |
| `In Progress` | Actively being executed (Phase 3) |
| `Blocked` | Paused on critical blocker, waiting for user input |
| `Completed` | All tasks finished and verified |
| `On Hold` | Paused due to external dependency |
| `Cancelled` | Plan abandoned, will not be executed |
| `Rolled Back` | Was applied but changes were reverted |

## Plan Immutability

Once status transitions to `Approved`:
- Sections above `## Execution Strategy` are **read-only** — no agent may modify them
- The architect's design, security considerations, and cost estimates are the approved contract
- If changes are needed, status must revert to `Draft` first (requires user approval)

This is enforced by agent instructions (`/task-manager` and `/iac-dev` both refuse to modify approved plan content). The visible status serves as a human-readable lock indicator.

## Priority Levels

| Priority | Use when |
|----------|----------|
| `P1 - Critical` | Production outage, security vulnerability |
| `P2 - High` | Blocking work, time-sensitive changes |
| `P3 - Medium` | Planned work, scheduled changes |
| `P4 - Low` | Nice-to-have, cleanup, optimization |

## Plan Section Order

Every `.plan.md` must follow this section sequence. The order is intentional — reviewers and users read top-down: why, what, how, risk, then execution.

```markdown
> **Plan** | `<plan-name>`
> **Status** | `<status>` | **Priority** | `<priority>`
> **Created** | `<YYYY-MM-DD>` | **Updated** | `<YYYY-MM-DD>`
> **Author** | `<author>` | **Environment** | `<environments>`
> **PR/Ticket** | `<link or —>` | **Rollback** | `<Yes/No/N/A>`
> **Phase** | `<current-phase>` | **Wave** | `<current-wave or —>`
> **Strategy Version** | `<integer or —>` | **Active Tasks** | `<task IDs or —>`
> **Blocked Tasks** | `<task IDs or —>`

# <Plan Title>

## Context                  — Why this change is needed
## Architecture             — Design, diagrams, service interactions
## Decisions                — Key choices with rationale (see table below)
## Task Dependency Table    — Task graph with agent assignments
## Implementation Tasks     — Granular, bite-sized steps with exact file paths
## Security Considerations  — IAM, encryption, networking, secrets
## Cost Impact              — Instance types, monthly delta, savings
## Resilience               — RPO/RTO, DR strategy (or "N/A" for non-critical)
## Testing                  — New/updated tests in support/Testing/? Recommend or skip with reason
## Success Criteria         — Measurable acceptance criteria
## Non-Goals                — What is explicitly out of scope
## Risks & Rollback         — Failure scenarios, rollback procedures
## Open Questions           — Unresolved items requiring user input

## Execution Strategy       — Appended by `/task-manager` (user-invoked after architect)
```

### Decisions Table

Capture key choices and their rationale. Prevents decision loss as plans evolve across sessions:

```markdown
## Decisions
| # | Decision | Rationale | Date | Revisable? |
|---|----------|-----------|------|------------|
| 1 | Aurora Serverless v2 over provisioned | Cost scales to zero in dev; meets prod burst | 2026-04-15 | Yes |
| 2 | Single NAT GW in non-prod | Cost saving; acceptable risk for non-prod | 2026-04-15 | No |
```

## Execution Strategy Section

After the user reviews the architect's plan, they invoke `/task-manager` which appends a `## Execution Strategy` section to the `.plan.md`. This section is structured and machine-readable. The template:

```markdown
## Execution Strategy
<!-- Added by /task-manager -->

### Task Breakdown
| ID | Name | Type | Agent | Model | Skills | Reads | Writes | Code Depends On | Execution Depends On | Complexity | Output | Validation |
|----|------|------|-------|-------|--------|-------|--------|-----------------|----------------------|------------|--------|------------|

### Dependency Graph
<!-- mermaid diagram showing task relationships -->

### Execution Waves
#### Wave 1 (Parallel Safe)
T1, T3

#### Wave 2 (Blocked by T1)
T2

### Critical Path
T1 → T2 → [final task]

### File Ownership
| Path | Owner | Access |
|------|-------|--------|

### Parallel Execution Safety
- Write-Write conflicts: [none | details]
- Read-Write conflicts: [none | details]
- Shared state: [none | details]

**Parallel Execution Safety: XX%**

### Model Assignment Summary
| Model | Task Count | Task IDs |
|-------|------------|----------|
```

**Rules for the Execution Strategy section:**
- Only `/task-manager` writes this section — no other agent modifies it
- The section is appended after the architect's content — `/task-manager` never modifies content above it
- The user approves the complete plan (architecture + execution strategy) before execution begins

## Compliant Plan Example (for reference)

This is what a correctly formatted `.plan.md` header and section structure looks like:

```markdown
> **Plan** | `add-aurora-cluster`
> **Status** | `Draft` | **Priority** | `P2`
> **Created** | `2026-05-08` | **Updated** | `2026-05-08`
> **Author** | `SHELYOG` | **Environment** | `staging, production`
> **PR/Ticket** | `—` | **Rollback** | `Yes`
> **Phase** | `1-Planning` | **Wave** | `—`
> **Strategy Version** | `—` | **Active Tasks** | `—`
> **Blocked Tasks** | `—`

